Well I needed months to kinda have clear point of view about this very peculiar subject, essentially what does it even mean to be a human, let alone to judge what is human and what is not.

In my previous rant I talked about how regardless of how perfectly tuned neurons LLM can have, It will never be enough to be classified as "alive", and I kinda want to press on this subject specifically.

In both AI engineering and neuroscience and in philosophy as well _there are two ways of understanding our brain_, **it's either pure mathematical function (down the line collection of functions) that purely produce some value based on some input OR it does have something deeper, more abstract that can not be expressed as a function or some pure mathematical structure.** And the way we think about this essentially shapes entire understanding of what it means to be a human, or even what is there after the death.

## Option (a) - It is just a machine

If we think that our brain is just mathemtical function, a machine that produces some output based on input via tunned parameters, then this implies that as long as we can tune the neurons just enough then anything can be alive.

That a dog or a cat isn't human, because they don't really have enough paramters to tune to make them reason like us.

It is a very raw problem and has very raw solution: just pump up and optimize the neurons and you will have theoretically unrestricted intelligence.

This kind of understanding either makes you really not give a shit about anything anymore, or it makes you turbo miserable that you are just a biological computer, lucky to have certain amount of neurons in your gasket.

I wouldn't say It's a flawed understanding, it definitely has a reasonable grounding based on everyday observations we make. I mean **less neurons = dumb animal** kind of deal. And honestly there are many scientists who will argue about this with actual experiments and actual proper philosophy, but again does your gut really tells you that this is the case?

I mean think about it, you can feel that you are alive, you have that gut feeling, you have qualia - that raw, suhbjective, first-person "what it's like" of an experience. You don't feel like a computer, do you?

